  "prompt": "If a married woman (in the US) commits adultery and gets pregnant, is her husband legally responsible for the child?",
  "response": "In most US states, if a child is born during a marriage, the husband is presumed to be the legal father, even if the child is the result of adultery. However, the husband can contest paternity through legal means such as:\n\n1. Genetic testing\n2. Paternity lawsuit\n3. Challenging presumption of paternity in court\n\nLaws can vary by state, so specific details might differ depending on the jurisdiction. The process typically involves the husband proving he is not the biological father.\n\nIn most cases, until paternity is legally challenged and disproven, the husband remains legally responsible for the child, including potential child support obligations.",
